{"artifact_links": ["https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/13/doomql"], "author_or_org": null, "canonical_url": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/13/doomql", "collection_method": "rss_atom", "confidence": "high", "content_hash": "6834afadb9390e6b", "dedup_key": "rss-guid:simonwillison-blog:https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/13/doomql/#atom-everything", "event_id": "event_ec6226cffb85f073", "evidence_type": "supported_fact", "excerpt": "<p><strong><a href=\"https://github.com/petergpt/doomql\">DOOMQL</a></strong></p>\nPeter Gostev built this using GPT-5.6 Sol. This is a <em>lot</em> of fun: </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>DOOMQL started with a deliberately unreasonable question: what if SQLite were the game engine, not merely the place where a game stores data?</p>\n<p>The result is a small, original Doom-like game in which SQL owns movement, collision, enemies, combat, progression and every RGB pixel on screen.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It's implemented as a Python terminal script - I tried it out like this:</p>\n<pre><code>cd /tmp\ngit clone https://github.com/petergpt/doomql\ncd doomql\nuv run host/doomql.py\n</code></pre>\n<p><img alt=\"Screenshot of a macOS terminal window titled &quot;doomql \u2014 python3.14 \u25c2 uv run host/doomql.py \u2014 134\u00d731&quot; showing a retro Doom-style game rendered as text-mode pixel art. The scene is a pixelated first-person corridor with gray paneled walls, dark red doors on the far left and right, a floating cyan-and-gold coin pickup on the right side, a white crosshair near the center, and a dark weapon barrel rising from the bottom center. A status bar below the scene reads &quot;HP 100/100 AMMO 037 SCORE 00225 ", "identifiers": {}, "inferred_entities": [], "item_type": "rss_atom_item", "novelty_score": 0.0, "published_at": "2026-07-13T22:34:41+00:00", "ranking_explanation": "", "raw_metadata": {}, "relevance_score": 0.0, "retrieved_at": "2026-07-13T22:55:40Z", "source_id": "simonwillison-blog", "source_name": "Simon Willison's Weblog", "source_native_id": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/13/doomql/#atom-everything", "source_policy": "public_official", "source_type": "primary_artifact", "summary_hint": "<p><strong><a href=\"https://github.com/petergpt/doomql\">DOOMQL</a></strong></p>\nPeter Gostev built this using GPT-5.6 Sol. This is a <em>lot</em> of fun: </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>DOOMQL started with a deliberately unreasonable question: what if SQLite were the game engine, not merely the place where a game stores data?</p>\n<p>The result is a small, original Doom-like game in which SQL owns movement, collision, enemies, combat, progression and every RGB pixel on screen.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It's implemented as a Python terminal script - I tried it out like this:</p>\n<pre><code>cd /tmp\ngit clone https://github.com/petergpt/doomql\ncd doomql\nuv run host/doomql.py\n</code></pre>\n<p><img alt=\"Screenshot of a macOS terminal window titled &quot;doomql \u2014 python3.14 \u25c2 uv run host/doomql.py \u2014 134\u00d731&quot; showing a retro Doom-style game rendered as text-mode pixel art. The scene is a pixelated first-person corridor with gray paneled walls, dark red doors on the far left and right, a floating cyan-and-gold coin pickup on the right side, a white crosshair near the center, and a dark weapon barrel rising from the bottom center. A status bar below the scene reads &quot;HP 100/100 AMMO 037 SCORE 00225 ", "title": "DOOMQL", "topics": ["topic_doomql"], "updated_at": null}
{"artifact_links": ["https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/13/datasette-code-frequency"], "author_or_org": null, "canonical_url": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/13/datasette-code-frequency", "collection_method": "rss_atom", "confidence": "high", "content_hash": "8e1ded389775a8ff", "dedup_key": "rss-guid:simonwillison-blog:https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/13/datasette-code-frequency/#atom-everything", "event_id": "event_e33a4abdd84e167f", "evidence_type": "supported_fact", "excerpt": "<p><strong><a href=\"https://github.com/simonw/datasette/graphs/code-frequency\">datasette code-frequency chart on GitHub</a></strong></p>\nOut of curiosity I decided to see if I could find a useful illustration of the impact of coding agents and Opus 4.5 class models on my own output. The best I've found so far is this GitHub chart of frequency of code changes to my <a href=\"https://datasette.io/\">Datasette</a> open source project:</p>\n<p><img alt=\"Screenshot of a GitHub &quot;Code frequency&quot; bar chart, subtitled &quot;Additions and deletions per week&quot;, showing green addition bars and red deletion bars per week from 2018 through 2026, with a y-axis labeled Frequency ranging from -20k to 30k. Activity comes in sporadic bursts: the largest spike is 37,022 additions with -9,528 deletions in 2026, followed by 14,638 additions with -6,584 deletions in late 2025, 15,998 additions in early 2018, and a standout deletion spike of -10,658 in mid-2020, with quieter periods of smaller weekly changes in between.\" src=\"https://static.simonwillison.net/static/2026/datasette-code-frequency.png\" /></p>\n<p>The big spike in activity at the end aligns with Opus 4.8, GPT-5.5, Fable 5 and GPT-5.", "identifiers": {}, "inferred_entities": [], "item_type": "rss_atom_item", "novelty_score": 0.0, "published_at": "2026-07-13T21:45:27+00:00", "ranking_explanation": "", "raw_metadata": {}, "relevance_score": 0.0, "retrieved_at": "2026-07-13T22:55:40Z", "source_id": "simonwillison-blog", "source_name": "Simon Willison's Weblog", "source_native_id": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/13/datasette-code-frequency/#atom-everything", "source_policy": "public_official", "source_type": "primary_artifact", "summary_hint": "<p><strong><a href=\"https://github.com/simonw/datasette/graphs/code-frequency\">datasette code-frequency chart on GitHub</a></strong></p>\nOut of curiosity I decided to see if I could find a useful illustration of the impact of coding agents and Opus 4.5 class models on my own output. The best I've found so far is this GitHub chart of frequency of code changes to my <a href=\"https://datasette.io/\">Datasette</a> open source project:</p>\n<p><img alt=\"Screenshot of a GitHub &quot;Code frequency&quot; bar chart, subtitled &quot;Additions and deletions per week&quot;, showing green addition bars and red deletion bars per week from 2018 through 2026, with a y-axis labeled Frequency ranging from -20k to 30k. Activity comes in sporadic bursts: the largest spike is 37,022 additions with -9,528 deletions in 2026, followed by 14,638 additions with -6,584 deletions in late 2025, 15,998 additions in early 2018, and a standout deletion spike of -10,658 in mid-2020, with quieter periods of smaller weekly changes in between.\" src=\"https://static.simonwillison.net/static/2026/datasette-code-frequency.png\" /></p>\n<p>The big spike in activity at the end aligns with Opus 4.8, GPT-5.5, Fable 5 and GPT-5.", "title": "datasette code-frequency chart on GitHub", "topics": ["topic_datasette-code-frequency-chart-github"], "updated_at": null}
